body.p:
 I am hesitant to point to my own work in a review, but there was a recent target article by Keisha Ray and Jane Cooper in the AJOB and subsequent responses that touches on some of the limitations of current bioethical conceptions of justice in relation to the environment and more-than-human world that the authors discuss. The response I co-wrote with Nicolae Morar engages with some of the limitations of utilising Beauchamp and Childress's anthropocentric conception of justice to attend to environmental and microbial injustices. Mayes et.al (2024

1
)

From the introduction two (or maybe three) explicit aims are identified:
To introduce both a theoretical and practical initiative that seeks to further ground solidarity between justice movements while simultaneously promoting a more-than-human-justice orientation for cosmopolitical flourishing;
Offer this framework as relevant to a broader bioethical, social scientists working on human-microbial relations [ sic], and philosophical research community;
(and for grounding policy). And another implicit aim:
To introduce the CSSM as the context for this research and a hub for interdisciplinary social scientific research into human-microbial relations. To adequately address four aims in such a short article is a tall order. Moreover, the first aim is formulated in complex language and deploys technical concepts that have rich scholarly genealogies that would require explicit introduction/discussion (such as ‘cosmopolitical flourishing’). In that sense, the article would benefit from a clearer articulation of the aims. I would suggest distilling the aim(s) in simple, straightforward language. What do the authors want us, as readers, to take away as the key aims of the letter?

